    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-04-11T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-04-11T11:00:00-05:00" n="20"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d20">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.65/530: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-04-11T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 11, 1938—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 11—1:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>296. Personal for the Secretary and Under Secretary.</p>
                <p>Spent last weekend with the King and Queen.</p>
                <p>Neville Chamberlain was there with his wife. He told me that the Italian
                    agreement was in fine shape; that the German agreement was not doing so well; he
                    found it impossible to come to grips with them and have them state what they
                    want. For instance, he said he had asked them what they wanted with regard to
                    colonies and <pb facs="0052" n="44" xml:id="pg_44"/> they tossed the question
                    off by saying that was something that could be settled in the next 6 or 10
                    years.</p>
                <p>I asked him if the failure of the agreement meant to him war or like difficulty.
                    He said “no”; that they were thoroughly convinced that Germany was in no
                    position as regards resources or reserves to go to war and they so knew. He
                    likened Germany to a boa constrictor that had eaten a good deal and was trying
                    to digest the meal before taking on anything else. Therefore he saw no
                    difficulties for the time being.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
